Experiment – 06 : Docker Commands for Content Management
AIM

Explore Docker commands for managing images, containers, files, and volumes (content management).


Exp-06

OBJECTIVE

Learn important Docker commands and flags.

Pull and run images from Docker Hub.

Build custom images with Dockerfile.

Manage containers and inspect logs.

Use Docker volumes to persist data.

Use Docker Compose to run multi-container apps.


Exp-06

SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS

Docker Desktop (Windows/macOS) or Docker Engine (Linux).

OS: Windows 10+ with WSL2, Ubuntu 20.04+, or macOS latest.

Terminal (PowerShell / Bash).

Internet connection to pull images.

Optional: VS Code for editing files.


Exp-06

QUICK REFERENCE — COMMON COMMANDS (with examples)

Note: Use a normal ASCII hyphen - in commands (not an en-dash).

1. Check Docker
docker --version

2. List Docker commands
docker

3. Pull image from Docker Hub
docker pull ubuntu

4. Run a container (interactive)
docker run -it ubuntu bash

5. Run container detached (background)
docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 nginx

6. List images
docker images

7. List running containers
docker ps


List all containers (including stopped):

docker ps -a

8. Stop / Start / Remove container
docker stop mynginx
docker start mynginx
docker rm mynginx

9. Remove image
docker rmi nginx

10. Execute command inside running container
docker exec -it <container_id_or_name> bash

11. View container logs
docker logs <container_id_or_name>

12. Build image from Dockerfile
docker build -t myapp:1.0 .

13. Login & push image to Docker Hub
docker login -u username
docker tag myapp:1.0 username/myapp:1.0
docker push username/myapp:1.0

14. Volumes — create, list, use, remove
docker volume create myvol
docker volume ls
docker run -it -v myvol:/data ubuntu bash    # mount volume into /data
docker volume rm myvol
docker volume prune   # remove unused volumes

15. Docker Compose (multi-container)

If your compose file is docker-compose.yml in current folder:

docker compose up --build -d
docker compose down


Or specify file explicitly:

docker compose -f docker-compose.yml up --build -d
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml down


Important flags

-d run in background (detached)

-e set environment variables (e.g., -e NODE_ENV=production)

-p host:container map ports

-v mount volumes

(Commands list derived from your experiment document.)
